        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 4-year-old boy from the Czech Republic who is brought in by his parent because of an acute cough that often brings up mucus, with intermittent wheezing and mild shortness of breath [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9, SNOMED:J20.9]. He has had a low fever at home and seems uncomfortable with a sense of chest tightness when coughing [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9]. At times he has brief choking episodes from phlegm in his throat and occasionally says his tummy hurts [SNOMED:J20.9].\n\nHe appears tired and clingy in the exam room but remains alert, interactive, and consolable. He breathes a little faster than usual and has an occasional asthmatoid wheeze when upset or after a coughing fit [SNOMED:J20.9]. His parent reports that the cough started after a recent cold-like illness, which fits with the common viral cause of acute bronchitis [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9].\n\n{patientName} lives with his parents and attends preschool, where he is around other children with frequent colds, making viral spread through coughing and physical contact plausible [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9]. He likes toy cars, picture books, and playing indoors with blocks. His family says he is normally energetic, but during this illness he has been resting more and drinking fluids with encouragement, in line with supportive care for acute bronchitis [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:cebf2413-ae59-4b96-8710-7da78542b5ee",
      "resource": {
